    "opinion": "As a 68-year-old retired woman living in Milan, I've seen how discussions about healthcare and COVID vaccines can become quite heated, especially with all the time I spend on social media. My approach is grounded in my life experiences and my Hindu beliefs, which emphasize compassion and understanding. When these topics come up, I find it's best to listen first. People often have strong feelings based on their own health journeys or what they've read online. I try to understand where they're coming from, even if I don't agree. My vocational diploma didn't cover medicine, so I rely on trusted sources like our local health authorities in Milan and information from my doctor. I've learned that sharing personal stories can be more effective than arguing. For instance, I might talk about how getting vaccinated helped me feel safer when visiting my two children and grandchildren, or how it allowed me to continue my volunteering work without as much worry. My knitting group has had some tense conversations about this, and I've found that staying calm and respectful, even when others get emotional, helps keep the discussion productive. My moderate conscientiousness means I take these matters seriously but try not to let them overwhelm me. Since I have good mental health, I can usually handle these conversations without too much stress, though I do sometimes need to step away if they become too negative. What works for me is focusing on practical aspects: how vaccines have helped our community in Milan reopen, how they protect vulnerable people I volunteer with, and how following health guidelines shows care for others. I don't try to convince everyone, but I do share reliable information when asked. Ultimately, I believe these discussions should be about supporting each other's wellbeing, not winning arguments.",
